Title: What My Bones Know: A Memoir of Healing from Complex Trauma
Author: Stephanie Foo
My Review:
I came into this book curious to learn more about Complex PTSD and how to be more empathetic in general. But I did not expect I would actually be able to relate and question some of my own experiences (even though I did not experience anything to that same level). It was really hard to listen to the author's recollection of her childhood and at times I would find myself mouth agape in pure shock between how horrid the author's parents treated her and how detached the events were described. For the rest of the book the author talked through her years of trying to heal after her diagnosis. I very much appreciated how candid the author was about her ups and downs, the methods that worked or didn't work for her, and especially her analysis of how race/mental health specifically for asians in America influence our childhoods and how that impacts how we deal with stress/problems as adults.
In addition, I would recommend listening to the audiobook. There is a section of the book where actual therapy sessions are included and I really appreciated the bravery it took to allow outsiders listen to something so intimate. As someone who hasn't been in therapy, this part of the book really gave me insight into what goes on during therapy and how it can actually help someone work through their thoughts and feelings. Overall, I appreciate the bravery it took to convey her story of healing and finding self-love.

Title: Sapiens: A Brief History of Humankind
Author: Yuval Noah Harari
My Review:
A few quotes I want to remember:

"A jumbo brain is a jumbo drain on the body"
"Vast majority of human communication is gossip"
"A child is born not from the sperm of a single man but from the accumulation of sperm in a woman's womb."
"We did not domesticate wheat, it domesticated us"
"The agricultural revolution was a trap. The luxury trap"
"From the advent of agriculture, worries about the future became major players in the human mind"
"History is something that very few people were doing, while everyone else was plowing fields and carrying water buckets"
"How did it happen that in the one species whose success was based on cooperation, individuals who are less cooperative, men, control those that are more cooperative, women,?"
"Money is more open minded than state laws, religious beliefs, and social habits"
"Farmers owned and manipulated plants and animals, could hardly degrade themselves by negotiation with their possessions, hence the agriculture effect, degraded animals into property."
"Monotheism explains order but is mystified by evil, dualism explains evil but is puzzled by order."

Title: The Way of Kings (The Stormlight Archive, #1)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review:
*4.5
I really enjoyed experiencing the ups and downs/getting to know the inner thoughts and emotions of each of the characters, especially Kaladin's and Dalinar Kholin's journey throughout the book. The writing throughout the book was great. Many of the quotes really stuck with me and I'll definitely have to go back and reread them. I know that this book is the first of many and that the world building is needed but at times progress through the book was slow. I still am looking forward to see how all the characters interact with one another and how everything comes together.

Title: Becoming
Author: Michelle Obama
My Review:
Coming from a vastly different background to Michelle, I was pleasantly surprised that I was able to relate to numerous parts of Michelle's life growing up. Her unconscious want to grab the next rung in life to gain the approval and adulation of those around her, to follow the 'obvious' path, when she was younger, rung very similar to my experience in pursuing college and then graduate school.
In addition, I enjoyed learning how she navigated life through college, life as a lawyer, and ultimately deciding to pursue a career that she felt she gained the most fulfillment from. Her doubt/questions about how much her job fulfilled her, while also acknowledging the reality of life's problems like money really hit home that feeling fulfilled in one's job was a privilege that not everyone can have.
Her recount of campaigning and Obama's presidency definitely gave me a fresh perspective on the pressures that politics has on the people that aren't explicitly involved. (audiobook - voiced by Michelle was great)

Title: The Handmaid’s Tale (The Handmaid's Tale, #1)
Author: Margaret Atwood
My Review: I had somewhat of an idea what this book would be about because I had seen small parts of the show. Because the book was hyped up so much for me I was disappointed with the book. Maybe I just didn't understand the themes and the underlying meaning in the text. I thought the way the story was told was unnecessary and somewhat confusing at points. While I liked some parts of the book like the interaction between the main character and her commander and Nick I was left wanting more. I was surprised at how abruptly the book ended and actually wanted to find out what happened. I thought the the books plot definitely had potential but it didn't fulfill my expectations.

My Review: I thought this book included some very adorable moments between the author and Juan Salvador, his penguin companion. However, I thought the book had its dry moments which made it hard to continue reading. Maybe it's just me but I thought the writing came from a perspective that I didn't really like.

Title: Rebel (Reboot, #2)
Author: Amy Tintera
My Review: I was skeptical of reading the second book considering that most sequels never live up to the first book however, to my surprise, I like the second book even more! I love how the author offers both Wren's and Callum's perspective in the book. The romantic scenes between them are so adorable. I also loved how the plot many unpredictable twists and turns. This series was great read!

Title: Reboot (Reboot, #1)
Author: Amy Tintera
My Review: Honestly, I haven't read a real book in a long time. So maybe I'm biased but I really enjoyed this book. The heroine provided a fresh new perspective, she was strong-willed and didn't do anything stupid even after falling in love. I liked how both Wren's and Callum's characters progressed and their relationship was so cute. Their romantic moments were to die for. I was apprehensive at first because Wren's character seemed to have a lot more emotions and feelings than her 178 number seemed to suggest to me, but I got over it because the story was intriguing. I'm looking forward to reading the sequel (hopefully it's just as good).
